Paragraph: (1) One cold February day, a man walked through the city. (2) The trucks on the streets splashed gray, dirty snow around. (3) The sky was cloudy and dark. (4) He felt very sad as he walked. (5) He had broken a law about mail because he didn't want his friend, Mr. Graff, to go to jail or make Mr. Graff's wife sad. (6) Now, he had to fire Mr. Graff, which made him even more upset. (7) He didn't like making people feel bad because he wanted everyone to like him.

 (8) Suddenly, Miss McGoun came rushing in, looking excited. (9) She said, "He's here!". (10) "Mr. Graff? (11) Please ask him to come in," the man replied. (12) He tried to sit calmly in his chair as Mr. Graff walked in. (13) Mr. Graff looked neat and was wearing glasses. (14) "Need me?". (15) Mr. Graff asked. (16) "Yes. (17) Please sit down," said the man. (18) But Mr. Graff kept standing and started talking, "You must have heard from Mr. Varney. (19) Let me tell you, he was not honest about the house rent. (20) Then, another person wanted the house for more money, and I thought it was best for our company to let Mr. Varney go. (21) I really didn't mean to do anything wrong.". (22) "Stan, I understand, but I've had many complaints about you," the man explained. (23) "I believe you don't mean harm, and a good lesson might help you do better. (24) But I can't keep you in the job.". (25) Mr. Graff laughed and said, "So, I'm fired! (26) I know I did some wrong things, but it's tough here.".

 (27) "Now, young man," the boss started to say.

 (28) "Please, no shouting," Mr. Graff interrupted. (29) "Everyone outside can hear us. (30) I know we've both made mistakes, but if I had a better salary, things would be different. (31) I just got married, and it's hard to have enough money.".

 (32) The man listened, feeling mixed up inside. (33) He knew firing Mr. Graff was hard, but sometimes, making tough decisions was part of his job.



